<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1845-04-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1845-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="30" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d30">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 24.</note>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Confidential.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Everett</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Calhoun</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1845-04-02"><hi rend="italic">April</hi> 2, 1845.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * * * * *</p>
                        <p>A person very high in the confidence of the government, but not belonging
                            to it, informed me a day or two since that he con*sidered the view of
                            the Oregon question lately delivered on the subject in Boston by Mr.
                            William Sturgis as fair and candid. <seg type="margin">Mr. Sturgis’s
                                pamphlet regarded by a friend of the British ministry as fair and
                                candid.</seg><seg type="margin">[28]</seg></p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>EDWARD EVERETT.</signed>
                        </closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">John C</hi>. <hi rend="smallcaps">Calhoun</hi>,
                                Esq., <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>